 {"id":"asupersync-1mm","title":"Implement ObligationRecord structure and registry","description":"# ObligationRecord Structure and Registry

## Purpose
Obligations are the operational enforcement mechanism for the “linear resource” discipline:
- reserve introduces a linear token
- commit/abort resolve it
- leaking a reserved token is a semantic error (caught in lab)

The registry tracks all obligations and ties them to:
- holder task
- owning region

## ObligationRecord (Plan-of-Record)
```rust
pub struct ObligationRecord {
    pub id: ObligationId,
    pub kind: ObligationKind,
    pub holder: TaskId,
    pub region: RegionId,
    pub state: ObligationState,
    pub created_at: Time,
    pub name: Option<String>,
}
```

## ObligationRegistry
Use internal arenas/indices (no slab crate required):

```rust
pub struct ObligationRegistry {
    pub obligations: Arena<ObligationRecord>,
    pub by_region: HashMap<RegionId, HashSet<ObligationId>>,
    pub by_holder: HashMap<TaskId, HashSet<ObligationId>>,
}
```

## Core Operations
- `reserve(kind, holder, region) -> ObligationId`
- `commit(id)` / `abort(id)`
- `on_task_complete(holder)` marks remaining reserved obligations as leaked (lab panic configurable)
- `pending_count(region)` gates region close

## Futurelock Detection (Lab)
A futurelock is “task holds obligations but stops being polled.”
- detect via `created_at` age + task progress counters
- surface as deterministic error in lab runs

## Acceptance Criteria
- Any task completion with outstanding reserved obligations is detected.
- Region close cannot complete with pending obligations.

