-{"id":"asupersync-izlc","title":"[EPIC-INFRA] Conformance Test Suite","description":"## Overview

Create a comprehensive conformance test suite that verifies runtime implementations adhere to the structured concurrency specification. This serves as both validation and documentation.

## Strategic Value

**Problem Solved**: Multiple runtime implementations (Lab, production epoll) must provide identical semantics. Without conformance tests, subtle behavioral differences can cause bugs that only appear in production.

**Why Conformance Suite**:
- Single source of truth for expected behavior
- Tests serve as executable specification
- Prevents regression when modifying runtimes
- Enables third-party runtime implementations

**Quality Assurance**: Conformance tests are how we prove correctness. They encode the invariants from the spec document as executable assertions.

## Test Categories

### Category 1: Region Lifecycle
- Region creation and nesting
- Region close waits for all children
- Orphan task prevention
- Region tree structure invariants

### Category 2: Cancellation Protocol
- Cancel request propagation
- Drain phase behavior
- Finalize phase behavior
- Cancel-safety of primitive operations

### Category 3: Outcome Semantics
- Four-valued outcome (Ok, Err, Cancelled, Panicked)
- Outcome joining rules
- Panic capture and propagation

### Category 4: Obligation System
- Obligation creation and discharge
- Undischarged obligation detection
- Obligation transfer rules

### Category 5: Budget Enforcement
- Deadline expiration
- Poll quota exhaustion
- Cost budget tracking

### Category 6: Two-Phase Commit
- Reserve/commit pattern
- Abort on cancel
- No data loss guarantees

## Test Infrastructure

### Conformance Trait
```rust
pub trait ConformanceTarget {
    type Runtime;
    fn create_runtime() -> Self::Runtime;
    fn block_on<F: Future>(runtime: &Self::Runtime, f: F) -> F::Output;
    // ... other required operations
}
```

### Test Macros
```rust
conformance_test!(region_close_waits_for_children, |runtime| {
    // Test implementation
});
```

## Acceptance Criteria

1. At least 50 conformance tests across all categories
2. Both Lab and production runtimes pass all tests
3. Tests are self-documenting (reference spec sections)
4. Test failure messages are diagnostic
5. Tests can run against third-party runtimes

## Dependencies

- Builds on existing Lab runtime
- May use oracles from chaos testing (Epic #5)

## Priority Rationale

